window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"You have been provided with a  meter rule a clam and a set of masses    (i) Clamp the metre rule to the edge of the bench such that 90 cm of the rule projects from the edges as shown in the diagram above. Ensure that the rule is capable of performing oscillatory motion  (ii) Fix mass  M  = 50 g at the end of the rule  (iii) Deflect the rule slightly that it performs vertical oscillations  (iv) Determine the time t for 10 complete oscillations  (v) Calculate the period T of the oscillations and evaluate T2  (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of  M  = 100, 150, 200, and 250 g. In each case record the corresponding values of t, T and T2. Tabulate Your readings.   (vii) Plot a graph T2 on the vertical axis against M on the horizontal axis. starting both axes from origin (0,0)  (viii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph and its intercept C on the vertical axis  (ix) Evaluate k = 4\u03c0s\\frac{4\u03c0}{s}s4\u03c0\u200b (Take \u03c0 = 227\\frac{22}{7}722\u200b)  (x) From your graph determine the period  T  when  M  is 180 g  (xi) State  two  precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"No of oscillations = 10  S/NM(g)t1(s)t2(s)t = t1+t22\\frac{t_{1}+t_{2}}{2}2t1\u200b+t2\u200b\u200b(s)T = tn\\frac{t}{n}nt\u200b(s)T2(s2)1506.906.906.900.690.4821007.857.857.850.790.6231508.758.758.750.880.7742009.559.559.550.960.92525010.3010.3010.301.031.06        (viii)  s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 1.06\u22120.48250\u221250\\frac{1.06-0.48}{250-50}250\u2212501.06\u22120.48\u200b = 2910000\\frac{29}{10000}1000029\u200b = 0.0029  C = 0.325    (ix) k = 4\u03c0s\\frac{4\u03c0}{s}s4\u03c0\u200b = 4\u00d72270.0029\\frac{4\u00d7\\frac{22}{7}}{0.0029}0.00294\u00d7722\u200b\u200b = 4334.98    (x) When M = 180 g, T2 = 0.85. \u2234 Period, T = &radic;0.85&nbsp; = 0.92 s    (xi)  Precautions:     1. I positioned my eye level with the meter rule's scale when taking readings to prevent parallax error and improve measurement accuracy.  2. I securely clamped the meter rule at one end to prevent any unwanted movement or slipping during oscillations, which could affect the consistency of results.  3. I performed the experiment in an area free from drafts or airflow to reduce air resistance, allowing more stable oscillations.  4. I checked the timing device for any initial zero error and accounted for it to ensure precise measurements of the period of oscillation.  5. I used small amplitude oscillations to maintain simple harmonic motion, ensuring that the period remained constant throughout the experiment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION (S.H.M)","question":"Explain simple harmonic motion","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Simple harmonic motion (SHM) is a type of periodic motion in which an object oscillates around an equilibrium position under a restoring force that is proportional to its displacement and directed oppositely, resulting in a sinusoidal motion with a constant period and frequency, as seen in systems like springs and simple pendulums.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"Define period and frequency with respect to simple harmonic motion.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"In simple harmonic motion, the period is the time taken for one complete cycle of oscillation, while the frequency is the number of cycles completed per second.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"You have been provided a rectangular glass prism, optical pins and other necessary apparatus. Using the above diagram as a guide, carry out the following instructions.    (i) Fix the drawing paper provide on the drawing board  (ii) Place the glass prism on the drawing paper and trace the outline, ABCD of the prism  (iii) Remove the prism, Mark point O and AB such that AO is about one-quarter of AB  (iv) Draw the normal through point O. also draw the incident ray to make an angle i = 25\u00b0 with the normal at O. fix two pins at P1 and P2 on the incident ray  (v) Replace the prism. Fix two other pins at P3 and P4 such that the pins appear to be in a straight line with the images of the pins at P1 and P2 when viewed through the clock along  DC   (vi) Remove the prism Fix two points at P3 and P4 and produce it to meet DC at l. Also draw a line to join  OI   (vii) With O as centre and using any convenient radius, draw a circle to cut the incident ray and refracted ray at E and H respectively. Maintain this radius through out the experiment  (viii) Draw the perpendiculars EF and GH. Measure and record d = EF and l = GH  (ix) Repeat the procedure for four other values of i = 35\u00b0, 45\u00b0, 55\u00b0, 65\u00b0 respectively. in each case measure and record d and l  (x) Plot a graph of d on the vertical axis against l on the horizontal axis  (xi) Determine the slope of the graph  (xii) State  two  precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Ni\u00b0d(cm)I(cm)1251.050.722352.001.253452.301.504553.002.005653.702.40        (xi) slope = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 3.5\u22121.22.3\u22120.8\\frac{3.5-1.2}{2.3-0.8}2.3\u22120.83.5\u22121.2\u200b = 2315\\frac{23}{15}1523\u200b = 1.53      (xii)  Precautions:     1. I ensured that all pins were placed vertically and securely to maintain accurate alignment throughout the experiment.  2. I positioned the pins precisely along a straight line to avoid parallax error and obtain clear, consistent readings.  3. I viewed the pins at eye level, ensuring alignment accuracy and minimizing observational errors.  4. I double-checked the pin positions before taking measurements to confirm they had not shifted or tilted.  5. I took multiple readings to increase accuracy and minimize the impact of any minor alignment discrepancies.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State Snell's law","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Snell's law states that the ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence to the sine of the angle of refraction is constant for any two given media. This constant is known as the refractive index. Mathematically, it can be expressed as: \u00a0     n = sin\u2061(i)sin\u2061(r)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(i\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(r\\right)}}sin(r)sin(i)\u200b","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Calculate the critical angle for a water-air interface. (refractive index of water = 43\\frac{4}{3}34\u200b)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Sin C = 1n\\frac{1}{n}n1\u200b = 143\\frac{1}{\\frac{4}{3}}34\u200b1\u200b = 34\\frac{3}{4}43\u200b = 0.75","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You have been provided with a constantan wire, a 2 \u038f standard resistor, an accumulator E, an ammeter A, a key K  and other necessary apparatus.     (i) Measure and record the emf of the accumulator provided  (ii) Connect the circuit as shown above  (iii) Close the key, read and record ammeter reading Io when the crocodile clip is not in contact with the constantan wire  (iv) Open the key. With the clip making contact with the wire, when L = 90cm, close the key, read and record the ammeter reading I. Evaluate L-1  (v) Repeat the process for L = 80, 70, 60, 50 cm  (vi) In each case read and record the ammeter reading and evaluate L-1 and tabulate your reading  (vii) Plot a graph of I on the vertical axis against L-1 on the horizontal axis  (viii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph and intercept c on the vertical axis  (ix) Evaluate k = cs\\frac{c}{s}sc\u200b  (x) Using your graph determine the current I when L = 55 cm  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate result","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/NL(cm)I(A)L-1(cm-1)1501.200.0202601.100.0173701.050.0144801.000.0135900.900.011        (viii) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 1.2\u22120.9250.02\u22120.011\\frac{1.2-0.925}{0.02-0.011}0.02\u22120.0111.2\u22120.925\u200b = 0.2750.009\\frac{0.275}{0.009}0.0090.275\u200b = 30.56  c = 0.52    (ix) k = cs\\frac{c}{s}sc\u200b = 0.5230.56\\frac{0.52}{30.56}30.560.52\u200b = 0.017    (x) when L = 55 cm (i.e. when L-1 = 0.018 cm-1), I = 1.11 A    (xi)  Precautions:   1. I ensured that the connecting wires were kept as short as possible to minimize resistance and reduce potential voltage drop across the connections.  2. I carefully inspected all instruments and connections beforehand to confirm that they were in good working condition and free from faults, ensuring reliable and accurate readings.  3. I checked for any signs of wear or loose connections in the wires to prevent fluctuations or inconsistencies in current flow.  4. I securely fastened all connections to avoid accidental disconnections during the experiment.  5. I kept the wires organized and free from tangling to avoid accidental movement that could interfere with measurements.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE AND ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"Explain what is meant by potential difference between two points in an electric circuit.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The potential difference between two points in an electric circuit is the amount of energy required to move a unit charge from one point to the other. It represents the work done per unit charge as it moves through the circuit, effectively driving the electric current between these points. Potential difference is measured in volts (V).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2006>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2006","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"State two factors on which the resistance of  a resistance wire depends","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. Length of the Wire  2. Cross-sectional Area  3. Material of the Wire  4. Temperature    1. Length of the Wire: Resistance increases with the length of the wire; a longer wire has higher resistance.  2. Cross-sectional Area: Resistance decreases as the cross-sectional area increases; a thicker wire has lower resistance.  3. Material of the Wire: Different materials have different resistivities; for example, copper has lower resistance compared to iron for the same length and thickness.  4. Temperature: Resistance generally increases with temperature, as higher temperatures cause more atomic vibrations, which impede the flow of electrons.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];